Here's the standard approach:

### 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Create matching `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` with the same keys but different values.

### 2. Load a default theme in `App.xaml`

```xml
<Application.Resources>
    <ResourceDictionary>
        <ResourceDictionary.MergedDictionaries>
            <local:LightTheme />
        </ResourceDictionary.MergedDictionaries>
    </ResourceDictionary>
</Application.Resources>
```

### 3. Swap themes at runtime in `App.xaml.cs`

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        ResourceDictionary theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast"  => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _               => new LightTheme(),
        };

        // Replace the merged theme dictionary
        Resources.MergedDictionaries.Clear();
        Resources.MergedDictionaries.Add(theme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }
}
```

### 4. Use `DynamicResource` in your XAML (critical)

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" Text="Hello" />
</ContentPage>
```

`DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) is what makes the UI update immediately when the dictionary is swapped.

### 5. Settings page trigger

```csharp
// In your settings page
void OnThemePicked(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    var selected = themePicker.SelectedItem as string; // "Light", "Dark", "HighContrast"
    ((App)Application.Current).ApplyTheme(selected);
}
```

### 6. Restore on startup — in `App` constructor

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ApplyTheme(Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light"));
}
```

**Key points:**
- Same keys in every theme dictionary → swap is seamless.
- `DynamicResource` everywhere → live updates, no restart needed.
- `Preferences` persists the choice across launches.
